< date>
1500501971054</date>
< Review>
For the price it's going to be hard to find any Indian or Nepali food this delicious *anywhere*, let alone San Francisco.

The service is quick and friendly. The man at the register was pleased with our choices but made suggestions, as well.

Be sure to order the Samosa Chat; incredibly tasty!

If you want something different than the usual Indian fare, order from the Nepali menu.

We tried the Newari Khaja which was a Nepali thali of sorts; I definitely recommend it, but be sure to order something saucy as well. Between the beaten rice and the ultra-crisp fried meat it can get pretty dry without some sauce.

You can probably dine in for lunch, but beware that the seating is very limited for busier hours, and it's not the nicest neighborhood. Otherwise take-out or delivery are great options, too.< /Review>
</record></dataset><record>

< Text>
I usually don‚Äôt review, but I couldn‚Äôt resist myself undoing the review for this palce.
First impression, very unclean, unstable dining table & not so welcoming staff.
Second impression,  We ordered chicken chowmin and Chicken mo:mo. Chowmin was ok, but the mo:mo was disaster. It was raw from inside, I could literally see the red meat lurking inside but the Chatney was good.
Never ever going to this place again.<//Text>

< Text>
This is a Charming little shop in coastal Oceanside on the Coast Highway. when I went there, I was welcomed by both of the ladies who were working, and invited to ask any questions that I might have pertaining to anything that they sold. They have a great selection of small stones as well as a good selection of shaped gemstones and such. They have some kitschy things as well if that is what you are into, but the reason why I'm giving it 4 stars is because other than the small stones, they did not have a very wide selection of much else and their prices are somewhat high. It may simply be that they have to charge more for things because of paying rent on the coast, but suffice it to say everything else about it is wonderful.my advice would be to either go there just to find out what it's like, or if you have more specific needs to call them first to see if they have what you're looking for. Have fun!<//Text>

I stayed at Fremont Hospital for 12 days. I was only allowed outside recreation twice. It was horrible. The weather was good but they didn't let me out. They asked if anyone wanted to go to the cafeteria at lunchtime but didn't say that we could go outside (to a tiny patio) after lunch in the cafeteria.

I felt very claustrophobic because it's a locked facility and going outside would have helped. Several staff in the hospital were often dismissive and some, very unprofessional.

This hospital was also very restrictive compared to other psych hospitals. We were not even allowed to keep toothbrushes in our rooms so we had to find often overworked staff to get the toothbrushes out of our lockers in order to brush our teeth.

Overall, this felt like a place that houses people, not a place to help with compassion and care.<//Review>

<Rate>1<//Rate>< review>
Please, please be aware of the care your children get here. Try to be knowledgable of your children's medication and dosages. Dr Kumar and I came up with a plan to titrate my daughter's medication more rapidly. Upon discharge, I learned that she was actually taking less than what she was when she went in for treatment initially. Now she's weeks behind where she is supposed to be and was there for literally nothing. This medicine has severe and potentially fatal side effects if not monitored properly and hospitalization would allow for quick treatment should a reaction happen, now we are weeks behind where we are supposed to be. I'm so frustrated.

Also, I made a plan with Nashin on Friday for discharge on Monday. They talked to my daughter about this plan and we were all on board. Monday morning I called to ask what time would be best to discharge and they said they had not worked that out but asked what time i was thinking. I told him 3 would work and he said someone would reach out and let me know. No one did. I came for visitation at 430 expecting to pick her up but she was not ready to go. I inquired to the nursing staff about discharge and they said they would find me shortly to work it out. 30 minutes later I asked again. I was then informed that she would be discharging tomorrow. To which I declined and said to get her ready for discharge. They made me wait for Nashin to talk about a plan for discharge and he wanted to discharge her the next day. I again declined as the plan had been for her to discharge that day and no one had informed me otherwise.

The communication is so poor, the negligent medical care is abhorrent. I'm blown away. And truly devastated by the damage caused. I will have to work out a new plan with her actual psychiatrist to get her up to a therapeutic dose of her medication quickly and make up for 10 days of lost time.

Your children deserve better than this place can offer. Get them stable and get them out! Be informed! Reach out to me if you don't understand what the doctor is telling you. I want to help. I'm lucky enough to be knowledgable about this, I cant imagine how people are taken advantage of who don't understand the treatment and medical language.< /review>

< user_id>
105370675361281217688< /user_id>
< user_name>
R D</user_name>
<date>1534999066074< /date><Rating>4</Rating>< review>
So far so good. My loved one was initially taken to John George and they had a wait for a bed which may have taken about a week or so. We advocated for our loved one to be moved where she could begin immediate treatment and get the help that was needed and Fremont Hospital seems like a good choice despite reading some of the bad reviews. We were uncertain of what to expect as we had never gone through this. Once she was there we called and were explained the policy about the 4 digit code. It's discomforting when you haven't seen your family in 3 days and you just want to make sure they're alright; but it makes sense and also helps with the patient being a decision maker in who they allow to contact them or find out anything over the phone. Dealing with mental issues being angry and not wanting anyone to see or speak with you is a possibility so we were more so thinking like what if we never get the code? How will we know what's going on?  We then learned that regardless if we have a code or not we are still given an opportunity to show up in person during visiting hours. That was a deep sigh of relief because if she was having a day where she didn't want to communicate with anyone she would at least see our faces hear us say I Love You! And know that we just didn't forget about her or were just leaving her there to fight her battles alone.

When we showed up 5 minutes before visiting was over the front desk staff was very courteous. They answered all of our general questions and called the charge nurse for the more detailed ones. A gentlemen explained about bringing in personal items and how we can store our belongings in a locker before visiting. By the time we were ready to see her the clerk advised us the charge nurse said she was sleeping and they dont like to wake them. Keep in mind we hadn't seen her in a couple days and just wanted to make sure she was ok and looked ok physically and by then my mom was a nervous wreck because she was told the same thing at the other facility. When your dealing with adult patients there is only so much you can do as a parent since they are no longer children and dont require parent consent for care.

We asked if someone could come down and at least speak face to face because we had never gone through this. The nurse explained that she could not leave the station and we can always come back the next day during visiting. We did not get upset as you have to understand a policy is a policy. I gave it a shot and respectfully explained my mom's concern and asked if she could at least just see her face through a window and advised that she will not disturb or awaken her and she would only be a moment. The charge nurse agreed and we both were able to go up! We respectfully followed all procedures and were escorted to where she was In her room sleeping. Glancing around I was impressed that the floor was very secure but it didn't give that prison security feeling. It was pretty clean and didn't have an extreme hospital feel to it. It looks as if most of the rooms have 2 beds. We traveled a short distance and then there she was! Even though we were there for just a minute it felt like a huge weight was lifted off our shoulders and even though she didn't see us we were there together spiritually. Upon leaving we thanked the staff and stopped to personally thank the charge nurse. She then explained about the 4 digit code and answered my mom's other questions and then we left.

I know this was a long read but hopefully this helped or was comforting to someone who is on the same journey we are. As we continue on I will post updates regarding our experiences and adjust the rating as needed. A BIG THANK YOU! To the staff so far as first impressions can tell you alot about what you'll have to deal with. We definitely hope this continues so we can have a strong foundation for our loved one.

God Bless!< /review>

<user>109668122027898929420< /user>< name>
Allison Medina< /name>
<date>1462637734756< /date><Rating>4< /Rating>< Text>
Im 14 years old , I thought it would be bad here . I was sent here in march , 2016. The nurses i had were great,  i look at all these comments and disagree with a huge amount of them here and yelp. They usually checked your rooms alot in the night . I felt safe there , didn't have any problems with any other patients , actually made friends. I was there for 2 days , but the downside is ... my doctor didnt help me . Just ask me questions (regular questions like hearing voices whose voice, what do you think we can do to help) and i answered them . And i really did want to leave , but when they didnt do anything,  its been what 2 months now . And i feel much more worse,  but dont get me wrong i loved that place . Except the doctor i had discharged me way to early.  Right when i got out i was on my way home and got some fast food (tasted delicious) and put in my earphones and thought about everything and i told my self everything is going to be okay. And i checked messages from friends etc . They didn't know where i was and were just scared. But i kept thinking. . What did i get out of this ? Friends that can relate to how i feel . Yea ... but i needed or NEED help . And later on i was at home and cried .. later on My mom talked to me like i was baby . Asking me if i needing anything i said im fine , she said how do you feel i said im good . And she would tell me i love you , dont do that to me again etc. I dont want to do that again to her cause she got in alot of arguments with people from there and also a crisis center. But i need help and they just didnt give me the help that i needed . And the visiting hours i liked . Only 45 minutes,  so your family only has enough time to tell you they love you and ask you questions and not yell at you,  but also some people dont get visitors and they dont want people to feel lonely cause no one visits them . I understand that fully . I hear voices,  when i was there , i told my doctor i hear a mans voice , kind of raspy . I didn't know how to explain it . But since that .. all i hear is my OWN voice . Telling me things . I havent heard the man .. i only hear myself saying mean things and i put in my earphones and just try to ignore them . It works sometimes but not all the time. I also cried to much , and recently i can only cry in the night before i sleep . my cries are random . I feel more like i just dont care about anything . School ... i get sent out of classes alot now , referrals, called home . And i get yelled at(of course) And i just dont seem to care as much as i used to.  And also the therapist. . They get annoyed very easily. I was only a level 1 , cause i never did anything in groups. . I just wish i got help , rather than just coping skills . . I guess it depends on the doctor you get.  4 star rating . Nurses 5.  Doctors 0. friends(patients) 5.
Therapist 0. Visiting hours 4. Help needed -10 fun +10</Text>

105422311471309460312< /UserId.>
<Name>Paul Volk<//Name>< date>
1359085369323<//date>
< Rate>
2</Rate>
< Review>
Went here to visit a friend committed to their inpatient program. This place just feels like something that escaped the lunatic asylum shutdown of the late 1900's. The facilities were clean but very old and packed full of negativity, as opposed to a positive environment for people in mental crisis (if I was there longer than a few days I'd need to be on some sort of medication too!). I understand that they are doing what they have to do but they are severely understaffed. The patients are treated somewhat fairly with the limited resources, but there is an overwhelming sense from the Psychiatrists that the patients are all crazy and need to be popping pills (which is definitely not an atmosphere to improve their condition). The goal of this place is to get patients in and out as quickly as possible while providing the minimum level of medical care possible, from overwhelmed Psychiatrists who if the patient is lucky spend 5-10 minutes a day with the patient. Oh and don't bother requesting a call from any of the docs because you won't get one, ever. Which is a testament to the complete lack of professionalism at this institution.

The case manager was pleasant to talk to and was the only one who seemed to have anything under control but ultimately did not facilitate any sort of after treatment outside of looking up outpatient facilities, which could have been done by anyone by spending 30 minutes on Google and Yelp.

In summary: Good quality of care? No. Blatantly Understaffed? Yes. Is that an excuse? Absolutely not.

Avoid this place at all costs.< /Review>

< userid>
107721878500814073502< /userid>
< name>
Luigi Chun<//name>
<time>1566680870422<//time><rating>5< /rating>< review>
Harper's Music is local music store we desperately need.

They carry all kinds of instruments, both new and used, varying from electric, acoustic, and bass guitars, band and orchestral instruments, synths, midis, drums... the list goes on. They have all accessories for said instruments. They also give lessons.

Xavier and Ricardo were both extremely helpful and knowledgeable with what they do, and what matters most is they put the customer first and make sure to meet your needs.

I brought in a flute that had a small sticky key problem, and Xavier patched it up without hesitating. I suppose it was a small fix. Furthermore, he did not charge me anything, probably seeing that he could establish a long-lasting relationship with a customer. This is how you build rapport with a customer! (But don't take this as an excuse to go in there asking for free repairs).

I am the new band instructor for my school and Xavier gave me the rates for both rental and purchasing. They work with schools to figure out better deals and prices for your students. They have a great Rent-to-Own program that you should definitely consider.

I will be doing business with Harper's from now on, as they prioritize serving the community first, no matter the cost and profit. They could nickel and dime us for everything but they don't. Give them your business so they stick around for even longer (they've been around since 1960's.)

Looking forward to working with your business in the future,

Luigi< /review>

< text>
I play guitar and the first time 2 times I went in I was very disappointed by the staff. Person was very aloof and did not want to be the there. My teenage son noticed it also. At the time Best Buy carried music gear and was down the street so if I need picks, strings or guitar cables I went there instead, especially because they were cheaper. I discovered Guitar Exchange in Bonita and went there and for the most part the experience was pleasant. Wanted to have my Guitar setup so I took it to Guitar Exchange and they said bring it back in a week. A week goes by and they are doing inventory and they can't do the setup. Bummed I called Harper's and the setup was half the price and I could take it that day and get it back in 2 hours. So after shopping several music shop I have learned that your experience is random and depends on who is working that day. The last 3 time I have been to Harper's has been great but unfortunately musicians are not known for being the most dependable people and it shows no matter where you go.<//text>

< review>
Short Answer: Do not use Mercari - I have learned my lesson.

Long Answer: I have used Mercari for about a year.  I have made 23 sales and bought 19 items.  I have 5 stars as both Buyer and Seller. Everything was okay for the past year.  Now, starting in Oct 1 they will taking charging an additional ~4% in extra fees and is no longer a cheaper platform than eBay.  Today, I just made a sale and sent a chat message to the Buyer asking for their phone number as I am shipping item by UPS and a phone number is required.  So to recap, I made a sales already on Mercari and now they deleted my chat message to the buyer stating that "I cannot ask for personal information on their platform".  This is nuts!  I tried to contact Mercari, but there is NO WAY to contact them.  I just de-listed all of my products I was selling.  I won't use thus platform any longer as they do not want quality Sellers with quality items.< /review>

<user_name>Ryan Tanner< /user_name>< Text>
I got Mercari to buy baby clothes for my upcoming baby, and wanted to also get a stroller. My mom wanted to help get us a stroller for our baby stroller, and she is not technically savvy, so we logged into the Mercari account I just set up, we found a stroller, great price, the lady we bought from was super nice, the whole transaction was seamless. I thought it was so nice that I would use Mercari for a lot of purchases in the future.

So why a 1 star review? Because after a few weeks Mercari shuts down my account. No idea why. No data. I tried to log in to find out, and it won‚Äôt let me log in. I try to go on their website to communicate with them, they won‚Äôt let me unless I log in, but I can‚Äôt. I try to find an email, but can‚Äôt find one. I try to find a phone number, none listed on their website. I had to google hunt some deep search of random blogs written by random people until I found someone who had procured their phone number. I call the phone number, it is 100% automated - you CANNOT get a live person. But, in that phone number, I got an email address for customer support.

I wrote to customer support, and get an automated answer. I think some live person answered after, but he was so robotic I thought he was a robot answer also (in hindsight I guess it was a human because it was signed by a name). They asked me to verify my identity, which I did, and believe me when I say it was the most secured identity verification process I‚Äôve ever done - I get more identity verification for a simple buying app than I did from any of my $10K+ credit cards or car loans - I mean for real? Face verification, upload drivers license, the whole 9 yards. Meanwhile NO explanation of why my account was closed.

Did they reopen my account? No. Why would they do something to assist a customer who legitimately wanted to buy and sell on their app? I mean, that would make good business sense, and so far they didn‚Äôt show any good business sense. What did they do? They sent me ANOTHER email saying I needed to verify my identity. Which I just did. So I did it again. And then I wrote a pretty harsh email saying I‚Äôd write a bad review if they didn‚Äôt help. They then responded saying that my account was closed because now my MOM needed to verify her identity through the same process, since we used her credit card to buy the baby stroller for my upcoming baby boy‚Äôs baby shower!!!! My mom is 70 years old, would not understand why she needed to do that, and it was just a joke.

For real?!?! I can‚Äôt believe this company will make it. It is a total waste of time. I suggest using apps or websites that actually give a darn about their customers, like Amazon or Ebay or OfferUp or something. Not Mercari. They are headed the wrong direction.< /Text>

<rate>1< /rate>< Text>
A couple weeks ago I purchased a hearth and hand toy treehouse from a seller on Mercari, it was shipped via UPS with tracking. When it arrived it was just shipping paper and label, the label said it was suppose to be 8 lbs but it definitely wasn‚Äôt more than a few ounces.

I contacted the seller and UPS right away. UPS started an investigation and concluded the item was ‚Äúdamaged in transit‚Äù
I did not rate the seller as I never received the item and instead contact Mercari support as it says to do in their terms of services.

Mercari refused to issue me a refund in the original form of payment. They only gave me Mercari credit which would expire in 30 days. Mercari said they had no way of knowing what happened to the package therefore they weren‚Äôt going to refund me to the original form of payment. I did not want the credit as my husband had already bought another one through EBay the same night that UPS didn‚Äôt show up (he wanted to shut me up about it) Mercari did not have another one in stock to just order since they don‚Äôt make this specific item anymore.

We have a video home security system and I sent screenshots to Mercari to prove how the UPS driver delivered the package since the UPS investigation wasn‚Äôt enough proof.

Luckily the seller had insurance and I was in contact with her throughout on Mercari. She seemed genuinely apologetic about the whole deal and I was wanting to send her all of the evidence of how it was delivered in case she has issues collecting the insurance through UPS ($120 item) but Mercari doesn‚Äôt allow images in the messages between seller / buyer.

I ended up making a claim with my bank. As I never received the item I paid for and did not want $120 in Mercari credit which would expire in 30 days as my husband purchased the item elsewhere.

Mercari froze my Mercari account (which has a balance in it from my sales) and refuses to unfreeze my Mercari account until I provide proof that I dropped the claim with my bank. They are holding my balance (which was the money I earned from selling AFTER they took their 10% cut).

I looked Mercari up on the better business bureau and it seems a lot of people have had the same experience as I have. If I had known how much trouble this would be I would have never signed up for Mercari. They take 10% from every transaction and offer no buyer or seller protection.<//Text>

< review>
Mercari is a safe place to shop. I have had no bad experience with this app. It has been a great experience I would have to say. It is a little different than the other sites in that you order, wait for it to arrive, and if satisfied you rate the seller and then they get paid. If it arrives broken you notify the company, and send several pictures to verify.
The employees at Mercari have always been courteous, helpful, and more than willing to help with whatever you need.
I've never experienced a bad seller there either. Of course, I always treat people the way I want to be treated, and usually, they reciprocate. So give it a whirl, and you'll have a good time!< /review>

<Date>1553564701084</Date><rating>1<//rating><text>How to receive FREE items by exploiting negligent Mercari policies!

I used to sell on Mercari with a 5 star rating, until they gave one of my products away. I sold a piece of sports memorabilia that the buyer reported damaged (8x10 protective plexi-glass sheet reportedly cracked). The buyer removed the triple layered protective foam sheets (which was more expensive than the $1 plexiglass sheet), took photos without the protective measures and sent it to Mercari.  Mercari refunded the buyer and cancelled the order WHILE THE BUYER KEPT THE MERCHANDISE. They responded with, "merchandise was insufficiently packaged" and hazardous to return.

I have shipped close to 100 (93 to be exact) of the same type items (all exact same materials/sizes/packaging with zero issues.

So, if you would like to receive items for FREE, remove any protective measures, file a damage claim stating broken glass along with doctored up the photos, and they will take the buyers word and give a 100% refund and let you keep it!

Sad, but true. Sellers beware!</text>< pictures>

< text>
This little pool area has several pools, and plenty of areas to set up for your time at poolside. Plenty of umbrellas and chairs, and a little food stand that made some really good food. My burger was on point and the drinks served here were very good. Prices were reasonable, water by cup is complimentary upon request, and the margaritas were so good during the hot day. I was not a fan of the cabanas here, they are very small and packed close to others. The girl who was tending my cabana hardly came by for water refills, and didnt tend to me as much as I would have liked. I tipped 20 off the top and 30 more when she closed my bill and left early, leaving no waters or clean around our area.< /text>

113024223646240430933</user>
< user_name>
Carly Russell< /user_name>
< date>
1534570793292</date>
<Rate>1< /Rate>< review>
NEVER AGAIN. Entered at 3pm today to grab a quick bottle of water with my 10lb service animal in my arms. Was yelled at and told to leave immediately by a mid 20's staff member with a name tag that read Judith but said her name was Christina when quieried. Note they have a walk-up window, but instead of kindly offering a solution to complete my transaction via the window, she instead fired off one comment after the next with absolutely no consideration for my "situation". I explained that it was nearly 100 degrees and it wasn't possible for me to leave the dog in the car. I explained that I simply needed a quick moment to complete my transaction. She refused. When I asked if she always treated people with service animals this way, she told me it was my fault because I didn't explain myself. She begrudgingly agreed to ring me up while continuing to fire off sharp and disrespectful commentary.  Keep in mind, at entry I wasn't asked..... she simply began yelling at me from behind the counter. She went on to tell me I should have tied the dog up outside. I expressed to her that there wasn't a suitable place to do so within view of the check-out counter and a small sized dog is easily capable of being taken. She then told me that was rediculous and expressed ZERO regard for me as a customer or an individual.  I'm a working professional, polite, and engaging with nearly everyone I encounter.  Thankfully I'm not routinely treated this way, but what I experienced today was downright harassment, verbally abusive in tone, approach, and bias. Service personnel who behave like this are why we're in a culture where people feel compelled to video disparaging and disrespectful treatment. It's wrong and it shouldn't be happening, period. It's easy to provide good customer service in nearly every situation, even when you feel a customer is doing something you think they shouldn't. I can respect whatever policy has been dictated to this employee, but use common sense and offer sensible solutions to someone who's just trying to spend money at your place of employment. I will be following up with the Chevron Corp regarding my experience at this franchise. Personnel should at minimum be transparent in identifying themselves, especially if they're going to specifically use another person's name tag and or identity to avoid accountabilty for bad behaviour. I wouldn't tolerate being spoken to this way by a stranger on the street let alone by a person representing a place of business.< /review>

<user_name>Mike Porter< /user_name>< time>
1568663686627<//time>
<Rating>5<//Rating><review>A true gem in the Wharf district of San Francisco.

My wife and I love to find small local places to dine when we travel, and the hotel concierge suggested this unassuming eatery for "really good sushi".   Grandeho's Kamekyo did not disappoint.  It's not cheap, but the rolls were fresh and service was prompt. Everything we wanted from a casual night out.

There are "hipper" places, and if that's your thing, you might be disappointed.  That's definitely not my thing, though, and it was an easy 2 block walk from our hotel located almost on top of Fisherman's Wharf.

It's worth noting that they do NOT participate in Monterrey Bay Aquarium's "seafood watch" program, so you can get some fish there that are on the "avoid" list.  This is probably no surprise to folks who know about the relationship of the Japanese to Pacific Ocean fishing, but if that's not a problem for you, it was an amazing evening.  If it *is* a problem for you, you can always take the SeaFood Watch app with you and refrain from ordering those items.

Overall, we had a wonderful evening of fresh fish.  I highly recommend a visit if you are in the area and in search of great sushi.< /review><pictures>None<//pictures><response>None</response><GmapID>0x808580e13cd891e9:0x8ef2442c19df560c<//GmapID></record>
</dataset><record>
< response>
None< /response>
< Text>
I don't like they abuse of the customer trust. The final bill includes the tip, which is 18%.
There is a sign at the entrance with low size showing you they will charge the tips. Obviously you will read it (if you have very good vision and you focus to these area) when you finish.
Plates are good but prices are high. And, as I said previously, you will get a big surprise when the ticket comes to your table.
I'm sure I'll never come back here.</Text>

1511191632804<//Date>
< rating>
4<//rating>
<gmap_id>0x808580e13cd891e9:0x8ef2442c19df560c< /gmap_id>< text>
Casual mom-and-pop sushi place with friendly service and fresh fish. The wife and I ordered Sushi Boat A ($60), which was the perfect amount of sushi for the both of us. Fresh, good quality fish, and the boat had a great mix of rolls v. sushi v. sashimi. They also brought out a few small complimentary side dishes for us (kimchi, bean sprouts, cucumber, etc.) while the sushi was being prepared, which was a welcome surprise. We came at 2PM on a Tuesday and there was only one other table occupied, which made for a nice quiet, peaceful meal. Will come back here next time I'm in the Fisherman's Wharf area!</text>

< Review>
The staff at Grandeho's Kamekyo is very kind and attentive. The prices are fair and the food is fresh!
I stopped in to eat dinner on my own and the restaurant wasn't particularly busy but they just started working on a large order for a big party. The server got me started on soup, communicated that it may be a few minutes for my entree, but quickly fulfilled my nigiri order even though the sushi chef was very busy.
The salmon nigiri is a larger portion of salmon than I've been used to and the scallops were amazingly fresh.
I definitely plan to make this a regular stop!<//Review>

< text>
We got 2 rolls of sushi--the Cherry Blossom Roll (salmon, cucumber, avocado and tuna) and the Bay Roll (scallop, crab meat, wasabi sauce, salmon and lemon). Both were delicious! I took off the lemon rinds that were on mine but it didn't take away any of the lemon flavor. I loooved the sushi! The chicken teriyaki was good. The tofu teriyaki was, according to my mom, "excellent," and she doesn't use that word to describe food often. My parents also ordered the tofu soup, which they said was good, but we were so full at that point that they could only eat one bite!

My family absolutely loved this restaurant, we ended up going twice! We felt very taken care of and well attended to. We celebrated our parents' anniversary the second time we went and they gave us a super cute fruit plate with little cubes of oranges and a really amazing duck made out of an apple! This place is wonderful and we highly recommend it.< /text>

<Text>This place is an oasis in one of California‚Äôs most beautiful regions. While you‚Äôre 5-10 minutes from the city, shops and restaurants, you feel like you‚Äôre in a remote country getaway. The terraces open up to fresh wooded air, quiet, and beautiful gardens with swans and flowing creek. It‚Äôs something quite magical. The rooms are modern and the staff is off the charts helpful and friendly. I came here to do a stop over from a road Trip and brought my bike with me. There are some great rides along Mulholland Dr, through the canyons, Griffith Park and Santa Monica beachside ride. So if you like the outdoors, this is yet another reason to stay here. It‚Äôs my favorite  destination in California along with the Ritz Carlton in Santa Barbara.</Text><rate>5</rate>< UserId.>

This property has just been renovated so you'll enjoy beautiful rooms and nice comfy bathrooms with a separate shower. I like the bar staff and the outdoor area is nice to sip a drink or have a cup of coffee.

<user_name>Expedia reviewer<//user_name><pics>None<//pics><text>The Hotel Bel-Air is a rarity in LA where most 5-star hotels offer friendly but casual (ie loose) service. The HBA staff is top quality and ride the fine line between friendly and formal with aplomb. The atmosphere, rooms, and facilities are the most private you'll find in LA without having to drive hours out of the city. The menus for the restaurant and in-room dining don't seem all the special at first glance but each seemingly regular item is prepared to perfection. This is not your standard hip and stylish LA 5-star boutique hotel. The HBA exudes comfort and class and makes you feel like you're on vacation at a resort. A true getaway in the city, this is a place you'll want to come again and again... and again.< /text>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
Clean, attentive to details which is what you expect here, and it is what you get. I have been coming here for many years. It is nice to see people that I have gotten to know over the years. The Fountain shop, Polo Lounge, are excellent. Worth noting- the CONCIERGE are the BEST. They do their homework, know the area. Great ideas to plan out your day, any sites, restaurants, or simply very trustworthy. If I got lost, they stayed on the cell until I was at my site, or safely back at the hotel. Having stayed at other supposed 5 star hotels, and asked their concierge questions, they did not know their area. I always compare, they are not the BHH.
Few concerns. But I know that they go above and beyond from my room to numerous details that make my trip more relaxing. Regardless of how busy they are, they are always kind, and run to bring my car right away. Centrally located. Easy access to head out in any direction.
Very highly reommend.< /Review>

<userid>105106526175686341179< /userid><Text>I am not sure if it is just because you expect the Hotel Bel-Air to be amazing and so it is, but, this was an amazing place to visit. It was a very cold night and the staff apologized and insisted I come back when it is warmer. The cold did not get in the way of the experience. As you enter and then cross the bridge it feels a little "Secret Garden" like. If I had a home in that canyon I would want it surrounded with the same beautiful foliage they have worked into the property. The staff is very professional and quick to help with anything I needed for the night. We hosted a group for a cocktail event and their food, wine and environment was perfect for mixing and mingling. It was cold outside where the couches were and though they had heat lamps it would have been good to have an indoor sitting option.
The renovated rooms are fabulous. High ceilings, beautiful furniture, good layout.
Our after hours were spent in the bar enjoying a subtle piano player and fireplace. It feels like a classic part of LA history.</Text>< date>

< text>
This pink palace, otherwise known as The Beverly Hills Hotel, has long been a favorite among Hollywood stars both old and new. In 1956, Gregory Peck and Lauren Bacall filmed Designing Woman by its pool. The Polo Lounge was a favorite drinking haunt for Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin, and the rest of their Rat Pack. Today, it remains one of the top places in town to see and be seen.

Insider Tip: Don‚Äôt miss the hotel‚Äôs Fountain Coffee Room, which has a curved soda fountain counter and iconic banana leaf wallpaper< /text>

<Text>I stayed here with my two dogs and anybody that travels with dogs knows how important it is that their dogs (or dog) are accommodated for and absolutely appreciate it when they are treated with respect as if they were people. Hotel Bel Air made every effort to make me feel comfortable and my dogs feel comfortable with very plush dog beds and individual dog bowls and water bowls and freshly packaged dog biscuits already in the room before we got there. The hotel however does not offer a specific dog food menu but will literally make exactly what you want and how you want it when ordering room service. The grounds of the hotel are absolutely gorgeous and have plenty of pathways and grass areas which is also a major plus for walking the pups.<//Text>< GmapID>

<time>1456444800000<//time><Rating>None</Rating><text>Overall, I loved this hotel--sparkling accommodations, lush gardens, lovely pool.  Staff courteous and helpful.  It is out-of-the-way, in a private, intimate setting.  Which is great, except that you are dependent on the hotel for meals, coffee, snacks, in short--everything--because it is located in a residential area that is miles from the city.  The cost of these extras exceeded the cost of the room (there is a daily charge for wifi--who charges for that anymore?).  Restaurant prices are exorbitant--which I wouldnt have minded if the food were good, but it was MEDIOCRE at best‚Ä¶and you cannot walk down the street to other restaurants.  No coffee-maker in the room (you have to buy theirs); no iron in the room (you have to pay for pressing); you get the idea.  Bring lots of cash, because everyone has their hand out.  My husband characterized it as the greediest hotel hes ever encountered.  That said, I still enjoyed it!  Next time, Id probably have food delivered.< /text>< Pictures>

1447272728804< /date>
<rating>1<//rating>< text>
They destroyed this once elegant and beautiful establishment.  I patronized the dining room on many occasions and, in fact, was there to partake of the last meal before they closed for a protracted renovation.  A few weeks after reopening, I went to see what was done.  I recognized almost nothing.  It's a disaster.  Having lunch, I realized I was being subjected to Queen's Freddie Mercury singing "Everyone Bites the Dust."  I love the song and Queen but during lunch at the Bel-Air?  I think not.  I have not returned and many others have done the same.  What a tragedy !<//text>

< Text>
After learning my brother was in a serious car accident in Saint Louis Obispo my wife and I decided to drive down to LA and check us into the Beverly Hills hotel. We wanted to take my mother's mind off my brothers accident. Explaining the story to the Hotel staff they checked us into one of the bungalows. Keep in mind I did not find the price for a room any higher then a quality hotel room. I work for hotels and this hotel had to top any hotel I've ever stayed at. The staff, the service, the decor. Everything about this property: is 5 stars. One example the hotel staff did for us was one night we were going out for dinner, the concierge provided a limousine free of charge. Another experience was in the Polo Lounge. One of the patrons claiming to be a producer was annoying by trying to cast my wife in a film. The manager of the Polo Lounge would not let us pay for any of our cocktails. Working for the hotel industry for over 20 years this is unheard of. I would like to thank the staff for five star hospitality.<//Text>

<Text>This place isn't any great place.

Hubby and and I came on a Friday night for DineLa. We were early and seated very quickly. There are booths and in the center are tables. Ambience is romantic with dim lights. It could get cold since seating is sort of an outdoor area patio but it's kind of covered with heat lamps. Hubby had to grab a coat.

Food was good but not great. Maybe it was the set menu for DineLa so I'll have to come back to try the other regular dishes.

Parking isn't great. There's street parking across the street if you come early enough but other wise there's valet with the hotel.<//Text>< pictures>

Prior to our arrival we were very excited for staying at the BHH- iconic, legendary etc. Upon arrival we requested if possible to have a room with a nice view. The front desk person assure us in a very condescending voice, the room we will be staying in is very nice and with a view, an upgrade from what our reservation was for. To our surprise, it was everything but! The room not only was very small, noisy being on the second floor, the worst was the tiny balcony with view of the wall and the dumpster. What a disaster! <userid>103206999838672326240< /userid><username>Kelly Watson<//username>< time>
1435226268414<//time>
<Rating>2<//Rating>< Text>
This review is strictly for the Polo Club restaurant. We finally went here from brunch yesterday after my girlfriend had been pleading for us to try it for months.

Needless to say, after going here once, we won't be back. Don't get me wrong, the grounds were lovely and the service was fine. It's just that the food quality was literally that of a Howard Johnson complimentary continental at a price point befitting its Beverly Hills address.

I got a chorizo omlette with hash browns. It honestly looked and tasted like it came out of a frozen package from Trader Joes. It was caloric sustenance, no more and no less. My gf got the french toast, which was slightly better, but again, a rather large letdown. For $24 a plate and $7 coffee (not to mention $9 valet service), we expected a great breakfast. Instead, we left feeling taken advantage of.

Go elsewhere. Almost anywhere is a better value.<//Text>

<userid>118182497469801829313<//userid><user_name>Mr. Zadok< /user_name><time>1404666485145<//time>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< text>
The best hotel in Los Angeles, probably North America, and quite possibly the entire world. A marvel to any luxury traveler with an eye for detail. They didn't miss anything. Sometimes when I'm here, I play a little game with myself where I try to find fault with some aspect of the the hotel and I can't do it. It's on the pricey side (but no more than any other luxury brand) and it's totally worth every penny. If you're looking for tranquility in the big city, world class service in the most luxurious and peaceful setting imaginable, then you've come to the right place.

I'd recommend this place as the perfect venue for an incredible date, to pop the question, to have the wedding at, or to go on your honeymoon at. I think you get my drift- it's one of the most elegant and romantic spots in the world. Everything here is world class.

The food is incredible. Honestly, they do room service so well here, that I often prefer to dine in than go out to some of my favorite restaurant in LA. It's kind of a funny thing, but the Hotel Bel Air may be home to the best Huevos Rancheros in the world (honorable mention for the steak frittes.) They also have an amazing bar area with one of the best bloody mary's I've ever had.

The rooms are really the masterpieces of the structural part of the hotel though. From almost any point in the room you can control the temperature, the lights (there are such convenient settings for them too,) or order any of the services the hotel has to offer. The miss no details, right down to the heated bathroom floors in winter. I'd invite anyone who's reconsidering a remodel of their home to come stay here for a couple of nights to take notes on features you might not have thought of, but will instantly recognize as perfection.

And the real masterpiece is the service. My only warning is that once you've been treated this well, you may not feel like anywhere else really lives up. For an incredibly busy person, this is the place for you. I have them unpack and pack my bags upon arrival and departure (they do about ten times a better job than I could and in a fraction of the time.) The concierge desk here rivals that of any in the world. Just tell them what you're interested in, and they'll supply you with an insiders itinerary for whatever it is you fancy. I saw them handling the medical needs of a guest so well yesterday that I secretly wished that they working in my doctors office when I got back home. They got me into an impossible restaurant within an hour of my asking and I can tell you from experience that doing these kinds of things is the norm out here.

Lastly, I know there's some controversy with the owner of this hotel, but after I thought about boycotting this place it occurred to me that I would most definitely not be doing any real damage to this man on the other side of the world who's worth 20 billion dollars. Instead, I would be hurting the people I've come to value most in this city. I'd imagine the people who are really suffering are the employees of this hotel, who are probably losing their jobs wholesale from this boycott thing. They're genuinely some of the most intelligent, empathetic, knowledgeable, and caring people in this city. So I am still very happy to stay here, because I'm for supporting them. I can understand the other perspective, and it's certainly valid, this is just my two cents.< /text>

110866235305619448548<//user_id>
<resp>None<//resp>< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< Review>
My company had a conference in Los Angeles (we make fake vomit and dog poo). Normally the Fake Vomit And Dog Poo Conference, FVADPC for short, is held in Pittsburgh in February, but this year due to a mix up with the booking agent, we ended up in the Beverly Hills Hotel. Now most members of FVADPC are of a working class bent. We like beer, pizza, football and whistling at construction workers. We also are, as a group, a bunch of practical jokers as our choice of profession no doubt informs. This seemed to rub the other hotel guests the wrong way, though I could hardly blame them I guess. One morning they are enjoying their 3oz $50 freshly squeezed orange juice, the next they are seated next a large sweaty man in a tattered sports jacket and a shopping bag full of fake dog poo. The staff were not well pleased either. I mean the worst a maid has to deal with on a daily basis is some questionably stained sheets and copious amounts of left over cocaine. The last thing they want to see when they pull off the bedcloths is a vast swath of quivering fake puke. (We used the deluxe version for one maid, the one with the bits of carrot and corn) However, the place was fantastic! The pool had water in it and you would not believe the muffins! Gus from Wisconsin ate 28 organic bran muffins at the first breakfast. He never left his room after that. We enjoyed the conference and the guest speaker, A Leslie Nielson look-a-like. Also we got to tour the famous homes of Beverly Hills and we were allowed into 3 stores on Rodeo Drive. Next year we are back in the Sunnyside motel in downtown Pittsburgh. It won't be quite the same.<//Review>
